<h2>Aging & Cellaring</h2>

<p>Unlike their red counterparts, most rosé wines are crafted for immediate enjoyment, with <strong>90% reaching peak drinking quality within 1-3 years of vintage</strong>. However, understanding proper cellaring techniques can help you maximize your rosé's potential and recognize when it's past its prime.</p>

<h3>Aging Potential by Style</h3>

<p><strong>Provence-style rosés</strong> from premium producers like Domaine Tempier or Château d'Esclans typically maintain freshness for 2-4 years, while <strong>Bandol rosés</strong> with higher tannin structure can evolve beautifully for 5-7 years. Spanish rosados from Rioja, made with Tempranillo, often improve over 3-5 years as their structured backbone supports longer aging.</p>

<p><strong>Light, fruity rosés</strong> from regions like Loire Valley or basic Côtes de Provence should be consumed within 18 months to preserve their vibrant acidity and fresh strawberry-watermelon character.</p>

<h3>Evolution Over Time</h3>

<p>Well-structured rosés develop fascinating complexity with proper aging. The bright pink hue gradually shifts to <strong>salmon or onion-skin tones</strong>, while primary fruit flavors transform from fresh berries to dried fruits and subtle spice notes. Quality rosés gain textural richness as phenolic compounds integrate, creating a more harmonious mouthfeel.</p>

<h3>Optimal Storage Conditions</h3>

<p>Store rosé wines at <strong>55°F (13°C) with 60-70% humidity</strong> in a dark environment. Unlike reds, rosés benefit from slightly cooler storage to preserve their delicate aromatics. Position bottles horizontally to keep corks moist, preventing premature oxidation.</p>

<h3>Aging vs. Spoilage Indicators</h3>

<p>Properly aged rosé maintains bright acidity and develops <strong>honeyed complexity</strong> while retaining fruit character. Warning signs of spoilage include brown discoloration, flat mouthfeel, or volatile acidity creating sharp, vinegary aromas. Trust your palate—if the wine has lost its refreshing quality, it's likely past its drinking window.</p>

