    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the difference between dry rosé and sweet rosé wines?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Dry rosés contain less than 4 grams of residual sugar per liter, resulting in crisp, clean flavors that showcase pure fruit and mineral characteristics. Sweet rosés, like White Zinfandel or some Provence styles, contain 12+ grams of residual sugar, creating softer, fruit-forward wines with candy-like sweetness. The production method—particularly when fermentation is stopped—determines the final sweetness level.</p>
