    <p class="text-gray-700">Serve rosé between 45-50°F (7-10°C), significantly colder than red wine but slightly warmer than most whites. This temperature preserves the wine's delicate aromatics while maintaining its refreshing acidity and preventing the alcohol from becoming prominent. Too cold (under 40°F) and you'll mute the fruit flavors; too warm (over 55°F) and the wine becomes flabby and loses its crisp character.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Should I age rosé wine or drink it immediately?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Most rosés are designed for immediate consumption within 1-2 years of release to preserve their fresh, vibrant fruit character. The wine's color will fade from pink to orange-brown over time, and the bright acidity that makes rosé so appealing will diminish. Only exceptional rosés from top producers like Domaine Tempier Bandol or serious Tavel wines can improve with 3-5 years of aging.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What are the biggest mistakes people make when buying rosé?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The most common error is choosing rosé based on deep, saturated color, assuming it indicates quality—when actually the opposite is true for most premium styles. Many people also buy rosé from the wrong vintage, selecting bottles that are 2+ years old when fresher vintages are available. Additionally, storing rosé in warm conditions or bright light destroys its delicate color and fresh fruit characteristics.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Which rosé wine regions offer the best value for money?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Portugal's Vinho Verde rosé offers exceptional value at $8-12, delivering crisp, low-alcohol refreshment perfect for casual sipping. Spanish Navarra rosé provides Provence-style quality at half the price ($12-18), while Loire Valley rosés from producers like Henri Bourgeois offer mineral complexity at $15-25. Avoid overpriced Hamptons or celebrity-branded rosés that charge premium prices for average quality.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What are good alternatives if I can't find quality rosé wine?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Light, chilled red wines like Beaujolais or Pinot Noir can provide similar refreshing qualities when served at 50-55°F. Dry white wines with good acidity, such as Sancerre or Albariño, offer comparable food-pairing versatility and crispness. For special occasions, consider Champagne rosé or Crémant de Loire rosé, which provide the elegance and celebration factor that still rosé often accompanies.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How can I tell if a rosé wine has gone bad or is past its prime?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">A rosé past its prime will show orange or brown tinges instead of fresh pink hues, indicating oxidation and age. On the nose, you'll detect sherry-like or nutty aromas rather than bright berry or floral notes, and the taste will be flat with muted fruit and reduced acidity. Unlike red wines that develop complexity with age, rosé simply loses its defining characteristics of freshness and vibrancy when it deteriorates.</p>
  </div>
